ave a partnership ethos that want to carry on that ethos, which one understands.  However, where one has either a new firm or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">business starting up or a venture that has grown to a point where they come to you for tax advice, which presumably at a certain size they do, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which structure </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">would you </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tell </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">them </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the most tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">efficient for a business to run in?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The first thing is that that is quite a complex decision.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ith the changes in corporate tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> recently</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, we have seen the corporate tax rate drop</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. F</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">om next year it will be at 20%, which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">n the G20 is the lowest</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">—</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">equal with </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Saudi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Arabia</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Russia</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.  In addition, we see from a corporate tax perspective </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">you have access to research and development tax credits.  There are a number of other items where the corporate tax items are different, so you would need to go through and properly evaluate what the overall return was going to be.  You would also need to look at the commercial objectives of the organisation.  One of the benefits of partnership is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">you can reward those at the top who are really driving the success of the business, and partnership share is a very important way of doing that, whereas in the corporate space you have the ability to go out for more debt.  If you are expanding into a business that needs capital</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">—</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">if you have capital requirements for</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, say,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> plant and machinery</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">—</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">rather than that which you can gather from the members of a partnership, you would look to go to a corporate vehicle.  Tax is but one of those, and the decision is not always</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> clear, which way or the other.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">From what you are saying, where an organisation need</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> a lot of capital expenditure or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">shows </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">comparable signs of looking like a corporate, where you see that as an LLP </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">you </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">would really have to question why they are an LLP. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> There is a challenge.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Under </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the LLP structure, it is not easy to generate capital.  There are ways to do that, and the limited liability part does make that easier, but it was originally designed with professional partnerships in mind.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q24 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Beddoe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Professor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Freedman, when the LLP was introduced in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2000, you, I understand, among</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> others, predicted that there were avoidance possibilities.  Given the way the legislation was drafted, do you think this ought to have been foreseen or countered by Treasury and HMRC?  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> It is always very easy, with hindsight, to say </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">things should have been done better, and I do not suppose I could have necessarily done better myself, but it was really the structure and the fact that it was being done in a hurry that worried me.  There were anti</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">avoidance provisions in the original legislation, but there was not very much thought about the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> aspects and the fact that many people were going to be partners rather than employees. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> If you look at the changes that are coming in this Finance Bill, as we look at it specifically, it derives from the fact that you have the presumption of self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employment.  That was something that was clearly at odds to the general partnership and may be one of the key drivers behind the situation we are in today.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Beddoe:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Do you think it was surprising that all members of an LLP would be treated as partners and so self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employed for tax purposes?  Was this the angle that you were concerned about? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> There was an unhealthy focus on the particular people who were asking for the legislation, which were the large partnerships of professional advisers.  There was not enough thought about how others might use those partnerships and that even the professional advisers might then begin to use it to reduce their tax.  However, mostly it was simply because there was not a wide enough overview of how this vehicle might be used when the legislation was introduced.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Generally speaking, we have significant differences between the way employees and self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employed people are taxed in this country and we have never allowed individuals to elect whether they are going to be taxed as one or the other.  It has always been dependent upon looking at the nature of their employment relationship to determine which they are.  However, one of the facets of the LLP was </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it was an indirect mechanism by which people could elect which form of taxation the</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">y were going to be subject to.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Your question triggers some thoughts </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the other part of your inquiry, which we may go on to later today, which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the making of tax policy and whether, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the current environment, you would have had a greater amount of consultation and a longer period in which to review and identify such concerns. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Beddoe:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> You mentioned in earlier evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">20,000 agricultural workers or fruit pickers or whatever it was.  Obviously, that was not, I assume, what the legislation intended to have.  Do you want to amplify that a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">little</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">?  There are gangs of agricultural workers that are outside of fruit pickers, but can you tell me a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">little</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> more about that?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I was reflecting, as was said before, on the ethos of partnership</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">being </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a partner in a business means </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that you share in both the upside and the downside, and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">at risk at times of loss or </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">at </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">times when you definitely do not have a guaranteed salary or items like that.  That is one of the key essences of being a partnership.  With the example that the OTS uses and John used last week of that 20,000, you would have to question whether they satisfied that particular test.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Beddoe:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> So such a structure really should have been foreseen. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> As Judith noted, it is easy to sit here with hindsight and look back at this.  I would like to think that the new focus on tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">policy-making</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> would give more time for those things to be foreseen and to give the kind of challenge, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we may come to later.  I still think </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury needs to enhance its challenge function on tax policy more generally and be able to really think through the impacts.  History has shown us that when we introduce a new tax regime or we make any change, it will be fine for the moment, but we always design tax policy based on the environment </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we have today and where we think it is going to be.  Generally, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">there </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is a different environment two, three or four years later, and that is when our tax rules are tested.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> As you say, we will come on to the whole process of consultation and so on.  Just going back to the 20,000-members point, was there an inherent fault in the structure of the original legislation, or should that particular instance, for example, have been challenged? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I personally believe that the presumption that the members of an LLP are automatically self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employed is one of the main causes of the challenge that we have here.  When my firm responded to the consultation that gave rise to the changes in this Finance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Bill, we said it should go back to the fundamental tests of general partnership applied to an LLP.  At a stroke, that would have dealt with the example of those 20,000</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">partners or so</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">called members of the LLP.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I remember when partnership law restricted it to 20, but that was some time ago.  W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hat do you think would be the result if the Chancellor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> had</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> looked at this in a completely different way and</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> had just simply said that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> will be applied to all earned income</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> That would result in a fundamental change to our overall tax system for, effectively, the self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employed, and would have driven up overall tax costs.  You would also have to look at the benefits, because there is a difference between the benefits that are received by those who are self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employed compared to those who are employed.  If I had</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> been asked that question while</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> sitting inside </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury, I would have most definitely asked Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs or KAI</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">—the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Knowledge, Analysis </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&amp;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Intelligence</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Directorate—</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to do an economic analysis to do that, so I will not presume to judge the outcome.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> That is the crucial question and answer</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> many of the problems, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">including </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the problem </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">your colleagues are looking at on the IR35 Committee: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">if we could just look at the root of the problem rather than always tackling the symptoms, and if we just had a proper study, as Mirrlees suggested and as the Office of Tax Simplification in its initial report on small businesses suggested, of whether we should in some way bring </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and tax charges closer together, given that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> is a tax, that would save an awful lot of trouble in the long run.  However, it is a very big job</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">t is not easy to do.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q25 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Drake:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> If I could declare an interest, I am an independent member of the Walker Guidelines Monitoring Group for the private equity industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Staying with this issue of employee or partner, and the folly that followed from the presumption of self</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">employment, the draft legislation still does not impose the general partnership law test to determine whether </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">someone is a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">partner or employee, and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">has these new mechanical economic tests—variable profits, influence over management and capital contribution.  Do you think it would have been simpler and more coherent to stay with or extend the general partnership law tests, and why do you think the Government did not stay with them?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> We do absolutely believe it would have been simpler to reinforce the tests.  At the moment, assuming these laws go through, we will have one particular treatment for the LLP structures and another treatment for English general partnerships and, indeed, for foreign partnerships, so we will have both rules running side by side.  Generally, we try to avoid having two systems that apply in a similar but slightly different manner.  As I mentioned, our response to the consultation specifically recommended that we reinstated the tests that applied to the English general partnership to the LLP.  HMRC has commented publicly in its response to the consultation that it did not believe that that would provide sufficient clarity because the rules were open for question.  That is an odd response given it has been clarified through the courts in a number of ways and, effectively, we are producing new rules that will have had no testing and will then themselves have to be clarified by the courts or by guidance.  We are potentially ending up again in a slightly unfortunate situation where we have some fairly broad legislation and that clarity </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">delivered not through legislation but through guidance, which is HMRC’s interpretation of the law rather than giving taxpayers the clarity they would expect.  So our recommendation was and remains that it should go back to the tried and tested rules that will still apply for</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> English general partnerships. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I am not sure that I would necessarily say it was simpler.  In a sense, the LLP in its current form is simple</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> it is just that we do not like the consequences that it produces, given the differences we have between taxing employees and those who are in an ordinary general partnership relationship.  If you have an entity where essentially you have a number of members and you have to try to draw a line between those whom you think are really in a relationship of partnership and those who are just employees, that is not necessarily going to be a simple thing to do, but it is difficult to think of alternative tests if that is the basic structure in which you have your tax system.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q26 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Just looking at the situation where you have partnership with</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> mixed membership, t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">he policy seemed to be to try </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> stop moving profits between the two</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> simply for</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> tax.  Does this happen in practice</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and is it for bona fide commercial reasons</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> or is it simply to take advantage of the situation for the benefit of reducing the overall tax burden</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Speaking for myself, I can say </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am aware that there are structures out there that use companies in this way.  I could not possibly say to what extent; it is a matter of general application or whether it meets particular circumstances.  It is obviously one way in which, through an appropriate structure, you can retain amounts within the overall entity and pay tax at the corporate rates</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and there may be perfectly good commercial reasons why you want to achieve that objective, whether related to the funding of the business or related to the way in which the members of the LLP are going to be rewarded.  Of course, from the Revenue’s perspective that look</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> like avoidance to the extent that amounts ultimately accrue to the benefit of the individual members rather than to the corporate entity, which is effectively an intermediate holding structure.  However, we could argue to the end of the day which are avoidance and which are not avoidance; it is just a use of the different forms and entities that we have and the way in which they are taxed.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Is it</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> to try to convert income into capital?  Is that the reason why you set up these structures with corporate membership?</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> It is very difficult to speak in general terms because one does not know.  These are not things that are necessarily the subject of general public knowledge; we are talking about private structures and so on.  Of course, some of them may be used to try to convert income into capital, some may just be being used to get the benefit of the lower corporate tax rate and others might be used for entirely nefarious purposes of putting profits offshore and not taxed at all.  I do not know.  It is just a function of having a variety of different structures taxed in a different way. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The other reason why you might have a corporate structure could well be for asset ownership or for property, where you may want a corporate that can sign leases or other commercial reasons as well, so there are other commercial reasons for why corporates might be useful.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">So you are saying that they are in addition to tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">planning reasons.  So there are tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">planning reasons why people do this</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> to have a mixed structure in some instances pu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">rely for tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">planning reasons.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> There are, in addition, commercial reasons for why there may well be a benefit to having a corporate in the overall structure.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Leigh of Hurley:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Do you think the proposed legislation will work in stopping the movement of profit around?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> We are still looking at the draft legislation at the moment</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. It </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is clearly out to consultation until the beginning of February.  It is a complex piece of legislation.  I can see where the Revenue are trying to get to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am not quite sure whether they will achieve it as yet.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I do not want to add anything to that, but </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">may I return to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Baroness Drake</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> point about the case law?  It seems to me that one of the problems—and the response of HMRC to the consultation responses shows this—is that they apply the case law in a certain way, looking at certain factors as if they were rigid, whereas in fact the case law is all about looking at the substance, not the form.  So it does not matter that people have holiday pay or not, which is one of the reasons they give for it being problematic, because that is only one small factor in the case law.  If they do not think that this case law is clear enough in the case of partnerships—LLPs—why do they think it is clear enough to use in the case of IR35?  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q27 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Drake:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Just staying there, perhaps I ought to declare </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am a member of the Employment Appeal Tribunal, so I hear some of these cases of whether someone is an employee based on their situation.  Do you think the new test could produce new anomalous results </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the status of people? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I am sure it will.  There will be a lot more cases.  There will be a difference between the person’s employment status for employment purposes and for tax purposes.  Where should </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> be there?  I do not know.  It will be with the tax, but is that fair?  If you are going to be judged on whether you are an employee or not for the purposes of certain benefits and you are paying </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">national insurance</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> as if you are an employee, how will</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> impact on you as an employment tribunal member?  I do not know.  Will you take it into account or will you not?  These are all questions </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we do not know the answer to and that raise uncertainties. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Drake:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Do you think it could lead to some significant LLPs restructuring their partnership agreements in order to build it explicitly around those tests?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> It is clear that they are all having to rethink their partnership agreements and before April as well, because they have set them up under certain rules and now they are all having to re</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">examine them.  That will not necessarily be about avoidance; it is just about knowing how their people are going to be taxed.  I have no idea what they will do, but they may well try to think of new ways of structuring.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I would endorse what Professor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Freedman has said.  Experience tells you that all these changes merely shift the ground on which the argument takes place, because you are not addressing the fundamental problem that underlies all this</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">d that is part of the problem.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To pick up the final point that was made by Lord</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Leigh, even if</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the change in the rules for mixed partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> is successful, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">there will inevitably still be attempts to structure on the basis of the new rules.  However, the balance that you are always trying to achieve in this area is between stopping what you do not like at the moment—and it is not always easy to see what is or is not liked at a particular moment—without inhibiting genuine commercial structures for which there is a commercial need to adopt maybe a partnership form or a mixed partnership form.  It is that very difficult balance between not inhibiting the commercial but stopping what you do not like that is the balance that is sought </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to be achieved.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Bilimoria:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Can we just pursue this?  Is there not an unintended consequence in that you can have a member of an LLP also being treated as an employee under the wording of the 2000</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Act?  How do you explain </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the fact t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hat you can have somebody who is a partner and also be—I think it is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ection</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">(4)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The question is to what extent that provision of the LLP Act 2000 has effect for tax purposes, given the specific deeming that there is for tax purposes that a member of the LLP is a partner for tax purposes.  There is a tension between what the general law in the LLP Act says and what the deeming for tax purposes is, whic</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">h you have drawn attention to. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Drake:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> This issue of the test for distinguishing partner from employee has obviously excited quite a few people.  How do you feel that that particular issue was dealt with under the new approach to taxation policy and consultation in particular?  Do you think it was fairly thorough or do you think that was a particular provision in the proposals that could have been iterated more thoroughly? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Reading the response to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">consultation, one of the key challenges in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-f