t thinking on this.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The important aspect of the Tax Professionals Forum is that it is designed to focus on the process rather than the substance of the policy.  Of course, at meetings there is a huge temptation to want to discuss the policy that has been adopted, but that is not really the function of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">orum and, from my perspective, I see that as a very important aspect of it.  Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a very good illustration of this tension between what one might describe as good policy and the responses in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the form </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">of good policy and the process by which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Government, for whatever reason, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">taken particular policy decisions and by what process </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">should press them forward.  In many respects, it seems to me that the mechanisms and processes by which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the Government consult on the policy and push</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> it forward to legislation have been working fairly well under the new arrangements, but of course that still leaves large question marks over whether it is the right policy or indeed, for example in the partnership area, whether it is addressing the right question.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I am not sure I recognise the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">point </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that our second report was less positive than the first.  They slightly focused on different items.  The first </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">looked</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> at the whole part of the tax policy and new approach and the way it was working, and the second looked in more detail.  In addition, with the second, we had had the protocol in relation to immediate announcements of tax policy, which we looked at.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Before coming to this Committee I re</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">read our two reports, and it was interesting to see that each of those reports had both good things and less good examples of engagement on tax policy.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">2011 one, we had things like the CFC as an example of really positive engagement throughout the process, and I may come back to that process in a moment.  Then we had some problematic ones in relation to things like disguised remuneration, which I know this Committee itself looked at in relation to the 2011 one.  There were some good and less good examples, and the same was true in relation to the 2012 ones.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">On things like, again,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the CFC, the statutory residence, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">non</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">dom examples</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the proposals were put through all five tests.  Nonetheless we had, dare I say, the pasty tax and other challenges in that one, so I think they both showed that the process is working.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tax </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Policy-making</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A New Approach</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, there is much more formality around how we go forward with tax policy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hat provides a real opportunity for many more people to be engaged in the debate</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and that is absolutely to the good.  There will always be examples, but the fact that I am citing examples of where it has dropped means that they are, almost by definition, the exception.  We are moving to a world where good policy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">making and good communication of that policy </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">becoming the norm, and that is a good result.  I hope that when we come to the 2013 review, which will be out shortly, we will find </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we are in the same position.  There are clearly some good examples and there are clearly some less good examples.  As Malcolm said, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">speaking in a personal capacity, one of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">my </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">concerns </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">be the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">four-week </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">consultation on tax and procurement that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">went</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> right up to a very hard deadline.  That </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">clearly </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">less </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">good for this forthcoming report, but I will </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">discuss</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> it with our fellow members.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Wheatcroft:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Would it be your theory that it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tends to work</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> less well when there is a wish to do something quickly?  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> When you are pushing something through very</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> quickly and you have less time </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to think, it clearly leaves you more exposed to lapses in the policy-making.  It is worth reflecting on what drove the creation of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">orum.  The tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">policy-making approach listed five areas of concern that set up the creation of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the forum</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and the overall approach.  If I may list them, there was the lack of a clear strategy for the tax system; consulting too late in the policy development cycle; the length and complexity of the tax code; uncertainty due to the volume and timing </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">of tax changes; and inadequate p</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">arliamentary scrutiny of tax legislation.  If I reflect on where that takes us in terms of </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tax policy-making</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, we have seen some clear strategy in relation to the tax system as a whole.  When I spoke to this Committee previously, we spoke about the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">corporate tax road map </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">providing a strategy of where the corporate tax system would go.  That has been a good</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> outcome of the policy approach:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> engaging with business and with interested parties about where the system would be.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">From personal reflection, I would like to see that developed further.  Rather than a corporate tax </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">road map</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, picking up </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">what Judith mentioned as well, maybe </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">there should be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">a business tax road map and a personal tax road map—something that gave you t</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">hat kind of focus on strategy.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The reports show that the second part, consulting late in the policy development cycle, has been improved.  As I already mentioned, there are a number of places where, to my mind, there have been lapses, but there is definitely improvement.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The length and complexity of the tax code is probably more a question for John</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Whiting with his OTS hat on.  I do not think we have seen much, if any, improvement of that; the pile of my books on legislation just grows ever higher.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">On the u</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ncertainty due to the volume and timing of tax changes</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it is very pleasant to know </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sufficiently in advance </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">when the Budget is going to be and to be able to see </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">some level of certainty there.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Finally, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the last point about increased </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">parliamentary</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> scrutiny of tax legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, C</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ommittees like you here and elsewhere have definitely improved the overall focus.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To reflect back to the question, I do think we are seeing some posit</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ive moves forward on tax policy-</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">making.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Wheatcroft:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Thank you very much.  Professor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Freedman, do you have anything to add to that?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Yes.  I am not in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the forum</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, but there is masses of consultation and that is all very well, but sometimes I am not sure that HMRC and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury know quite what to do with it.  Unless you go out consulting with some clear background knowledge so that you can evaluate what is coming back, there is a danger that you lose your way.  I am not saying that this is necessarily deliberate lobbying</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">t might be, but it might just be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">technical points </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">being made that are then put into the legislation—I have seen examples of this—where they do not really fit, because the people who have received the responses think it must be a good point if it has come from clever people but they do not really see where it fits.  That can mess up the legislation quite badly, so there needs to be quite a lot of knowledge in order to evaluate the consultations, and so a road map would be helpful.  However, you also need quite detailed knowledge, and sometimes the people working on the consultations, who are all very, very bright, have just not had long enough in the area to know about that detail and so mistakes are made that way.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The other thing I would say is that we are also still not very good at looking at these tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">policy changes in a wider context and in a holistic context.  We are not looking at benefits legislation at the same time as we are looking at tax</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e are not looking at employment law</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e are not looking at partnership law when we are changing partnerships.  There is not enough joined-up </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">overnment here, so that can cause problems</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. One </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">of the problems with this partnership legislation was that it was being led by DTI, as it then was, and perhaps there was not enough input from HMRC.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Wheatcroft:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The silo approach. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Professor Freedman: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Yes.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Wheatcroft:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Gammie, do you have anything to add? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> No, I think Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sanger has dealt fairly comprehensively with what I would say on the matter.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q29 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sanger, you mentioned the pasty tax.  There will always be little bits of the Finance Bill that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">deal</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> with what are seen as particular problems or particular opportunities or for political reasons</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">here will always be those sorts of things.  You would draw a distinction between that, including some that we used to call “lollipops”, and the wider tax structural changes and so on for which the consultation process was really meant.  You are not suggesting that every small tax change should be subject to consultation.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> No, I am not suggesting that every small tax should be subject to consultation.  However, there is a fundamental challenge when you make any change to the tax system, because it will necessarily change the environment</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and tax motivate</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> behaviour at the margin, so it is sensible to review.  Sometimes it is dangerous to proceed with policy changes unless they have been consulted on, because having that knowledge about how the tax system applies in practice is really important.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I would </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">look at the way </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury and HMRC are structured right now</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">e used to have an environment where</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the Inland Revenue and Customs and Excise, in those days, owned tax policy changes and the role of Her Majesty’s Treasury was to have that strategic view and to challenge the outcome of Inland Revenue and Customs and Excise.  If </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">anted to implement a particular change, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">would ask the Inland Revenue experts and the Customs and Excise experts to design the change</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> and then </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">would engage in discussion and challenge what that change was going to be.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am not sure whether the so</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">called pasty tax is an example of this, but there is a danger in the current system that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury has taken on board quite a lot of the people from HMRC, and they now have a kind of policy origination function as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the function </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">they used to have in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">relation to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">policy strategy and policy challenge.  There is a danger that with a policy originated inside HM</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury it may not get to, if you like, the depths and the specialists within HMRC who might well be able to say, “In practice, that is not going to work in my esoteric part of the tax system”.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">f policies were more owned at the HMRC level, you might find that some of the idiosyncrasies of the tax system that would just </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">lost on policy officials sitting in HM</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury, however hard they were to try, would be picked up and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">perhaps </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">dealt with before </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">they were </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">released in draft legislation or consultation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q30 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Blackstone:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The 2011 report of this </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ub</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ommittee recommended that the Government should commit </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">themselves </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to post</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">implementation reviews, which would be independent, when large tax changes had taken place.  The recommendation was not taken up by </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I do not think any of us were on the Committee at the time.  I wonder whether you could tell us to what extent the Government’s existing monitoring and evaluation arrangements meet the objectives and standards of independent review.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> By definition, they cannot be independent in the sense that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the implementation </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is being done by people who may be principally responsible for their operational implementation and who will have a particular perspective of provisions.  In that sense, I would have said that there was still considerable scope for a much greater degree of independent standing back and looking at what we have.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Just to pick up the five headings that Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Sanger referred to in relation to the policy objectives, as he notes it would be very difficult to say </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we have had much success in limiting the scale of legislation that is introduced and the sheer scale and complexity of that legislation, but it is very difficult to assess that anybody at any officially recognised level stands back and reviews that.  One assumes that reviews occur within the Treasury and the Revenue, and it may be that they can </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">come and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">speak to this Committee in a bit more detail about what they do, but I would suspect that they come at a lot of these issues with a rather more limited eye than I certainly would think desirable in trying to tackle some of the ongoing problems of the tax system.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Blackstone:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Is it the intention of the Tax Professionals Forum to take on post</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">implementation reviews of this kind?  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I do not think that is in our remit.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The extent to which this might be done </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">is obviously an aspect of the discussion that has occ</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">urred at some of the meetings, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">but I do not think it is one of our specific remits.  In some ways, it does not have to be done at an official level.  The Institute for Fiscal Studies and the Tax Law Review Committee, to an extent, can and do take on this sort of role, but inevitably external reviews of that sort may have less impact than if you had something within the institutional framework to see that it is done.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Blackstone:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> You are not arguing for your remit being changed so that you could encompass this sort of work. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> I do not think I would necessarily be against a change in the remit so that it included that, but you have to recollect that we are a voluntary body dealing with these things.  Generally speaking, given the scale of the consultation that Professor</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Freedman has referred to, we have our work cut out just monitoring what is going on let alone standing back and reviewing what </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">was</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> put in place a few years ago.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> It </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">may be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">worth reflecting that the Treasury’s own </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Green Book</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Appraisal and Evaluation in Central Government</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, suggest</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> that all policy-</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">making that it imposes or requests of other </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">government departments </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">follows the so</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">called ROAMEF approach</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">rational, objectives, appraisal, monitoring</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">“EF”</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">—</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">evaluation and feedback.  So I think it is perfectly right that others should be looking to Treasury to follow its own advice in relation to the “EF” of ROAMEF.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Blackstone:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> What has happened since the 2011 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">sub</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">committee’s </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">report does not lead any of you to believe that there is no issue here</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  There is an issue and it is something </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the Committee ought to pursue.  Would I be right in concluding that from what you have said? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> As Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Gammie said, there is little evidence to the outside world of those reviews being undertaken.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">They </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">may be happening inside </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury and HMRC, but it would be good </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the outcome of that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to be far more visible</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.  Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">going </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">back from this Committee to the Tax Professionals Forum, our role is, as Mr</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Gammie set out, to look at the way policy is made and those last parts will encourage us to engage further on the “EF”.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Baroness Blackstone:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> If they are doing these reviews, are you implying that they really ought to be published so that they </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">can be more widely scrutinised?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chris Sanger:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> There will be some things in relation to the reviews that may need to be confidential, because they may need access to taxpayer information, but there should be a natural part of reviewing the outcome of legislation and that can only be to the good. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> You can be sure that these are questions that we will be asking of HMRC and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Treasury when they come in front of us as part of this inquiry.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q31 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Wakeham:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> In your last few answers, you have answered most of the points that I was going to ask in my question, so my question is pretty simple: do you think </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the proposals for changes in the partnership legislation live up to the high standards that you think have been achieved in the past and are intended in the new policy? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Do you mean in the way in which they have been implemented? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Wakeham:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The way they have been discussed and promoted.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Malcolm Gammie:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The consultation process is obviously continuing.  There are elements of it that have not necessarily quite </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">come up </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to the standard that one would hope to have seen, but we are in an ongoing process, so perhaps one should reserve final judgement on that until we see what the final product is.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> That sounds a very tactful answer, if I may say so.  Can I thank all three of you very much indeed for yet again giving us the benefit of your experience and views?  You are very welcome to stay on for the next witnesses if you wish to do so, but thank you, because you have also raised points that we will be raising later in other sessions, for example, with HMRC and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="fon